00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:32.770
Well , your nose is filled with lots of blood
vessels with only a thin membrane to protect

00:00:32.770 --> 00:00:33.770
them.

00:00:33.770 --> 00:00:38.010
Often this membrane gets torn or irritated.
and boom, your face is dripping with blood.

00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:41.600
there’s two kinds of nosebleeds, anterior
and posterior.

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:44.870
Anterior nosebleeds are in the part of your
nose called Kiesselbach's triangle and are

00:00:44.870 --> 00:00:49.539
triggered by an irritation to the lower nasal
septum, the thin membrane that separates your

00:00:49.539 --> 00:00:50.539
nostrils.

00:00:50.539 --> 00:00:51.949
Kids most often get this kind.

00:00:51.949 --> 00:00:54.670
I think they spend too much time digging for
gold.

00:00:54.670 --> 00:00:58.640
More common in adults, posterior nosebleeds
originate further back and higher up in the

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:00.449
nose, to where arteries are.

00:01:00.449 --> 00:01:03.330
Sometimes they can be severe enough to warrant
medical attention.

00:01:03.330 --> 00:01:04.480
So how do you get them?

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:09.690
Well the nose is in a vulnerable place, so
a bump or a punch might do some damage.

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:13.900
Other than that common irritants include cold,
high altitude, dry air.

00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:17.330
Anything that dries out your nose leaves the
lower nasal septum vulnerable.

00:01:17.330 --> 00:01:20.790
A little scratch from a fingernail can start
the blood gushing.

00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:21.790
Although.

00:01:21.790 --> 00:01:26.010
spontaneous nosebleeds might be a sign of
hypertension or infection disease, or even

00:01:26.010 --> 00:01:29.520
more rarely Vitamin C deficiency, anemia,
or heart failure.

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:33.810
Those are common causes, what about more strange
ones you ask?

