00:01:55.382 --> 00:01:56.382
So how do you stop a nosebleed?

00:01:56.382 --> 00:01:59.400
Dr. Mary Pickett, an instructor in medicine
at Harvard Medical School says a pinch will

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:02.970
do the trick and you should treat all nosebleeds
like an anterior one.

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:05.990
Pinch your nose halfway between the tip of
the nose and the bridge.

00:02:05.990 --> 00:02:08.270
Lean forward so the blood doesn’t drip down
your throat.

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:09.910
Hold tight for five minutes.

00:02:09.910 --> 00:02:11.810
If that doesn’t do the trick, repeat.

00:02:11.810 --> 00:02:14.280
On rare occasions you might need to go to
the hospital.

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:19.250
More complicated methods include cauterizing
the blood vessel using silver nitrate.

00:02:19.250 --> 00:02:23.760
Researchers from Detroit Medical Center won
an ig nobel prize in 2014 for using an old

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:24.900
school approach.

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:28.400
The award celebrates silly and surprising
but practical research.

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:32.240
The researchers couldn’t stop a young girl’s
nose bleed with traditional methods so they

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:33.280
tried salt pork.

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:37.090
They say that "there are some clotting factors
in the pork ... and the high level of salt

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:39.360
will pull in a lot of fluid from the nose”.

